XFX RX 5700 XT Triple Dissipation

BEND THE RULES Great gaming experiences are created by bending the rules. The AMD Radeon RX 5700 Series GPUs are powered by the all new RDNA architecture and are designed from the ground up for exceptional 1440p performance, exceptional power-efficiency for high-fidelity gaming. Equipped with the latest 8GB of GDDR6 high-speed memory and PCI Express 4.0 support, delivering twice the bandwidth.

Overview

Introducing the new XFX Triple Dissipation 5700 XT. Built with style and dynamic cooling power in mind to yield lower temperatures and heightened performance that adapt to the intensity of the moment.

Get the very best FPS the 5700 XT Series can deliver. Thanks to the 2 90mm fans and 100mm fan and copper GDDR Heatsink the 5700 XT Triple Dissipation Ultra stays cool and quiet, allowing you to achieve higher boost clocks.

Equipped with dual BIOS. Choose between high performance mode or lower fan noise for your desired gaming experience.

    Chris Cameron
    5.0 out of 5 stars The best value for a 1440p and maybe any GPU now... period
    Reviewed in the United States on December 8, 2019
    Size: 5700Style: Double DissipationVerified Purchase
    The XFX RX 5700 DD Ultra is an interesting card. It's priced ($299 Cyber Monday '19 sale) very competitively and manages to even undercut a lot of the inferior reference blower designs which... ba dum tsssss... blow. There's nothing too wrong with the reference 5700's unlike a lot of the superhot XT models, but there's not really any headroom for OCing or anything else, which is fine if you just want to unbox and game. However, with the price of this 5700 being the same or sometimes less, it's really a steal over a reference card. The card looks ok, much better than last gen XFX designs and looks more like their nice, sleek looking R9 280x cards which were one of my favorite looking. It does have a lot of cheaper plastic surrounding the heatsink still- coming from the terrible Thicc original design- but there are some good improvements and if you really didn't care about aesthetics you could just remove the plastic for better cooling. Unfortunately XFX made some horrible errors in their earlier Navi GPUs, but they have since done a better job revising the design and cooler efficiency and making direct improvements reflective to customer and reviewer observations. This model is supposed to have the revised copper edition cooler from the Thicc II which is a much better albeit still not the best design, but on a 5700 it does the job decently, and there's headroom for over clocking and something else that really makes this card worth getting even at it's original $329 sale price. The card has a boost clock of 1750 which is respectable and out of the box can challenge a 2060 Super or 2070 and surpass that in AMD leaning titles. The card does also support a Dual BIOS feature as well, and if you're familiar with previous AMD GPU's you might know where I'm going with this. I'm of course talking about the 'something else' that makes this card and all 5700's a real value if you're ok with putting in a little work. 5700's are exactly the same card as the much pricier XT model minus the higher clocks and 4 disabled CU's. So, with this exact card and many others you can perform a BIOS flash to a matching XT model BIOS and essentially turn your regular 5700 into an XT model (minus the 4 CU's of course) and regain a lot of lost performance by unlocking the clock speeds. This lets you get close to 2000mhz core clock and with those settings this card can meet- and sometimes beat- a 2070 Super or a 2080 especially in games that AMD does well in like Red Dead 2 where 15-20fps can be gained by flashing. Do be aware though that this almost certainly voids the warranty and even though the card has a dual BIOS that can be switched if anything did go wrong, there is still a tiny, tiny chance that you could turn your card into a brick. Either way though the card is really a decent buy even just out of the box and is backed by a 3 year warranty. There isn't a single other GPU solution that can put out this much performance for the price and save easily $100 or more over other similar performing cards. At $300 it easily beats a comparably priced 2060 and if you don't care about RTX or production (Radeon VII) then this really is the best deal for 1440p. There might be better options lower than $300 for 1080p, but if you have the extra $50-100 or are considering 1440p or a 144-240hz monitor then it can't be beat and you get some future headroom out of it as well. All in all an excellent buy coming from a 1070ti, definitely recommend this card for your next upgrade!

    2.0 out of 5 stars Big Card Doesn't Mean Good Cooling
    Reviewed in the United States on November 24, 2019
    Size: 5700Style: Double DissipationVerified Purchase
    I bought this gpu but ended up returning it. It worked fine in terms of usage, drivers and was a good value but it has its issues. First off, this card is chunky, its takes up nearly three full slots and it's fairly long too, as a result the card sags a bit, but that happens to any large gpu. The big issue with the size is that it doesn't cool well for a three slot card, my memory temp peaked up to 96c, the other temps were suitable but again not great for its size.

    After I returned it, I bought a PowerColor RX 5700 (non XT) Red Dragon and it only takes up two slots, is about 2 inches short in length, and it cools better at the same noise level roughly. The memory temp on the PowerColor doesn't even hit 80c.

    With all of that said, apparently XFX is putting a copper memory plate on their newer gpus, that may only pertain to the XT varraints of this card, but the copper should cool the memory somewhat better if newer versions of this card have the copper. I did not take mine apart but from looking at it, but mine appeared to have the stainless steel from looking at it.

    5.0 out of 5 stars Best Bang for Your Buck for Non-Reference RX 5700
    Reviewed in the United States on November 17, 2019
    Size: 5700Style: Double DissipationVerified Purchase
    Recommend booting this thing up with a single monitor on an HDMI cable on your first install and downloading the latest drivers directly on the AMD site. After that this thing exceeded all my expectations and now works flawlessly on my dual 1440p monitors (One Display Port and another HDMI). With the new AMD drivers, I did the auto-undervolt in AMD Wattman settings (although some prefer to undervolt or overclock manually) and this thing stays cool as a cucumber and I can still play any AAA title I've tried so far on Ultra (The Division 2, Outerworlds, and Kingdom Come Deliverance) so far. Huge upgrade from my RX 480 Sapphire Nitro + I had prior. I read you can also flash this with the XFX 5700 XT BIOS for another 10% performance boost but I think for now I don't even need to mess with that. I don't feel like the fans are really any louder than previous card even under load but then again I always game with headphones for what it's worth.

    Karolina
    2.0 out of 5 stars Build quality and driver Issues unresolved since 2019.
    Reviewed in the United Kingdom on July 22, 2020
    Size: 5700 XTStyle: Triple DissipationVerified Purchase
    Got the card for my quiet build, replacing an MSI armor 1070.

    First one I ordered had a rattling fan (one out of three), never ever had a fan ratle out of the box, returned it, the replacement card did not have this issue.

    The XFX card features zero rpm fan technology, meaning that fans turn off, untill the card reaches 60 degress, then they start spinning untill the temperature drops to 50 degrees. However, due to an unresolved driver issue, with forum posts dating as far as mid 2019, on some single monitor setups, as well as most dual monitor setups, the card's VRAM runs at max frequency, which in turn means that the card runs hot on idle.

    Basically, after you turn the computer on, the card quietly reaches 60 degrees ON IDLE, then the fans start spinning, but because of high idle temps, caused by max frequency VRAM, the temperature never falls below 55 - 54 degrees, which in turn means that the zero rpm quiet fan thing never kicks in.

    After a recent driver update, it is impossible to set a custom fan curve with 0 rpm, as the card's bios does not allow the fans to spin under 15%. So only the card can decide when the 0 rpm thing kicks in. Why?

    Performance-wise, the card runs ok, not too loud, not too hot, and a visible improvement over my old 1070.
    If fan noise is not an issue, and the max VRAM frequencies and higher temperatures are not a concern, this could be a decent upgrade at the current price of ~350, however, at this price, I would like to have something that works as intended.

    Maybe team red has hit the nail on the head with its CPU's, the GPU's however are not quite there yet. I mean year old driver issues, cmon AMD, show some effort.
